#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:556
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <command>ifconfig</command> and <command>route</command> tools are "
"obsolete. Use <command>ip</command> instead. <command>ifconfig</command> , "
"for example, limits interface names to 9 characters."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_wicked.xml:563
#, no-c-format
msgid "Configuring a Network Interface with <command>ip</command>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:622
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<command>ip</command> is a tool to show and configure network devices, "
"routing, policy routing, and tunnels."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:626
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<command>ip</command> is a very complex tool. Its common syntax is "
"<command>ip</command> &nbsp; <option><replaceable>OPTIONS</replaceable> "
"<replaceable>OBJECT</replaceable> <replaceable>COMMAND</replaceable></"
"option> . You can work with the following objects:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_wicked.xml:635
#, no-c-format
msgid "link"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:637
#, no-c-format
msgid "This object represents a network device."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_wicked.xml:643
#, no-c-format
msgid "address"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:645
#, no-c-format
msgid "This object represents the IP address of device."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_wicked.xml:651
#, no-c-format
msgid "neighbor"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:653
#, no-c-format
msgid "This object represents an ARP or NDISC cache entry."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_wicked.xml:659
#, no-c-format
msgid "route"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:661
#, no-c-format
msgid "This object represents the routing table entry."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_wicked.xml:667
#, no-c-format
msgid "rule"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:669
#, no-c-format
msgid "This object represents a rule in the routing policy database."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_wicked.xml:675
#, no-c-format
msgid "maddress"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:677
#, no-c-format
msgid "This object represents a multicast address."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_wicked.xml:683
#, no-c-format
msgid "mroute"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:685
#, no-c-format
msgid "This object represents a multicast routing cache entry."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: net_wicked.xml:691
#, no-c-format
msgid "tunnel"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:693
#, no-c-format
msgid "This object represents a tunnel over IP."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:699
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If no command is given, the default command is used (usually <command>list</"
"command> )."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:703
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Change the state of a device with the command <command>ip link set</command> "
"&nbsp; <option><replaceable>DEVICE_NAME</replaceable></option> &nbsp; "
"<command/> . For example, to deactivate device eth0, enter <command>ip link "
"set</command> <option>eth0 down</option> . To activate it again, use "
"<command>ip link set</command> <option>eth0 up</option> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:710
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"After activating a device, you can configure it. To set the IP address, use "
"<command>ip addr add</command> &nbsp; <option><replaceable>IP_ADDRESS</"
"replaceable> + dev <replaceable>DEVICE_NAME</replaceable></option> . For "
"example, to set the address of the interface eth0 to 192.168.12.154/30 with "
"standard broadcast (option <option>brd</option> ), enter <command>ip addr</"
"command> &nbsp; <option>add 192.168.12.154/30 brd + dev eth0</option> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:719
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To have a working connection, you must also configure the default gateway. "
"To set a gateway for your system, enter <command>ip route add</command> "
"&nbsp; <option>gateway_ip_address</option> . To translate one IP address to "
"another, use <command>nat</command> : <command>ip route add nat</command> "
"&nbsp; <option>ip_address</option> &nbsp; <command>via</command> &nbsp; "
"<option>other_ip_address</option> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:726
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To display all devices, use <command>ip link ls</command> . To display the "
"running interfaces only, use <command>ip link ls up</command> . To print "
"interface statistics for a device, enter <command>ip -s link ls</command> "
"&nbsp; <option>device_name</option> . To view addresses of your devices, "
"enter <command>ip addr</command> . In the output of the <command>ip addr</"
"command> , also find information about MAC addresses of your devices. To "
"show all routes, use <command>ip route show</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:735
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For more information about using <command>ip</command> , enter <command>ip</"
"command> &nbsp; <option>help</option> or see the <systemitem>ip(8)</"
"systemitem> man page. The <option>help</option> option is also available for "
"all <command>ip</command> subcommands. If, for example, you need help for "
"<command>ip</command> &nbsp; <option>addr</option> , enter <command>ip</"
"command> &nbsp; <option>addr help</option> . Find the <command>ip</command> "
"manual in <filename>/usr/share/doc/packages/iproute2/ip-cref.pdf</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_wicked.xml:748
#, no-c-format
msgid "Testing a Connection with ping"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:749
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <command>ping</command> command is the standard tool for testing whether "
"a TCP/IP connection works. It uses the ICMP protocol to send a small data "
"packet, ECHO_REQUEST datagram, to the destination host, requesting an "
"immediate reply. If this works, <command>ping</command> displays a message "
"to that effect. This indicates that the network link is functioning."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:757
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<command>ping</command> does more than only test the function of the "
"connection between two computers: it also provides some basic information "
"about the quality of the connection. In <xref linkend=\"ex.basicnet.manconf."
"ping\"/> , you can see an example of the <command>ping</command> output. The "
"second-to-last line contains information about the number of transmitted "
"packets, packet loss, and total time of <command>ping</command> running."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:766
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"As the destination, you can use a host name or IP address, for example, "
"<command>ping</command> &nbsp; <option>&exampledomain;</option> or "
"<command>ping</command> &nbsp; <option>&wwwip;</option> . The program sends "
"packets until you press <keycombo><keycap function=\"control\"/><keycap>C</"
"keycap></keycombo> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:773
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If you only need to check the functionality of the connection, you can limit "
"the number of the packets with the <option>-c</option> option. For example "
"to limit ping to three packets, enter <command>ping</command> &nbsp; "
"<option>-c 3 &exampledomain;</option> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_wicked.xml:780
#, no-c-format
msgid "Output of the Command ping"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: net_wicked.xml:781
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"ping -c 3 &exampledomain;\n"
"PING &exampledomain; (&wwwip;) 56(84) bytes of data.\n"
"64 bytes from &exampledomain; (&wwwip;): icmp_seq=1 ttl=49 time=188 ms\n"
"64 bytes from &exampledomain; (&wwwip;): icmp_seq=2 ttl=49 time=184 ms\n"
"64 bytes from &exampledomain; (&wwwip;): icmp_seq=3 ttl=49 time=183 ms\n"
"--- &exampledomain; ping statistics ---\n"
"3 packets transmitted, 3 received, 0% packet loss, time 2007ms\n"
"rtt min/avg/max/mdev = 183.417/185.447/188.259/2.052 ms"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:790
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The default interval between two packets is one second. To change the "
"interval, ping provides the option <option>-i</option> . For example, to "
"increase the ping interval to ten seconds, enter <command>ping</command> "
"&nbsp; <option>-i 10 &exampledomain;</option> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:796
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"In a system with multiple network devices, it is sometimes useful to send "
"the ping through a specific interface address. To do so, use the <option>-I</"
"option> option with the name of the selected device, for example, "
"<command>ping</command> &nbsp; <option>-I wlan1 &exampledomain;</option> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:803
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For more options and information about using ping, enter <command>ping</"
"command> &nbsp; <option>-h</option> or see the <systemitem>ping (8)</"
"systemitem> man page."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: net_wicked.xml:809
#, no-c-format
msgid "Pinging IPv6 Addresses"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: net_wicked.xml:810
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For IPv6 addresses use the <command>ping6</command> command. Note, to ping "
"link-local addresses, you must specify the interface with <option>-I</"
"option> . The following command works, if the address is reachable via "
"<literal>eth1</literal> :"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: net_wicked.xml:816
#, no-c-format
msgid "ping6 -I eth1 fe80::117:21ff:feda:a425"
msgstr ""

